text_answer.content:
Numerical is too easy for 1th grade.
Key Details question 1 is great, since all the answer choices reflect information discussed in the passage but only one actually answers the question asked. I'd like to see more questions like this, especially in 11th and 12th grade.
Key Details question 3's answer is the only one that lists two items.
Key Idea question E is a rare answer that's too broad.

For the inference question, being able to measure precisely doesn't necessarily equate to strong mathematical skills. Precise measurements relate more to attention to detail.
E is a reasonable answer. While I agree that limited might be a bit too strong and 'primarily came from' could replace 'was limited to,' the passage does clearly state he chose to take the vocational class because he'd spent years watching carpentry on TV. Added how much he had to learn and it's reasonable to think he hadn't had much hands on experience before the class.

text_answer.content:
Vocabulary sentences 1 and 6 are going to be rough since there's limited context to differentiate the concepts in the sentences themselves and I doubt most 10th graders will know what trasngenic or recombinant mean.
The last paragraph is a little jumpy. I'd probably switch the last two sentences. There's also no reason to introduce a big topic like modifying human genes in the last paragraph. Instead I'd discuss other topics more related to the overall topic, like the legal issues surrounding GMO patent ownership.
I don't really like any of the answers in the Key Idea. The ongoing societal debates isn't introduced until the conclusion, so it's not a part of the overall main idea. I did predict C originally, but that answer is a little hyperfocused on the laboratory when the passage is more focused on the applications. Maybe "The modification of DNA sequences in living organisms through genetic engineering has transformed multiple sectors."
For the analyzing information question, what are therapeutic substances? The passage doesn't mention therapy at all.

For the inference, "Starting in 2022, U.S. manufacturers are required to label products containing GMOs, reflecting the growing public interest in transparency regarding genetic modification."
E is a reasonable answer. The passage discusses how plants are modified to, broadly speaking, grow better - such as the apple which has a longer shelf life. This allows more usable plants to reach the store, improving sales down the line.

text_answer.content:
Vocabulary questions 1 and 2 might be a little rough. 10th graders likely will have heard the word depolymerization and have a basic idea of the meaning, but they won't know the full definition. I doubt they'll know what pyrolysis is. I suspect the only way students will be able to work through the two is because of the prefix pyro and the inclusion of heat in sentence 1. The passage doesn't even clarify the definitions of the words.

For the inference, "These developments are particularly crucial given the only 9% of plastic waste globally is currently being recycled, highlighting the urgent need for more effective processing methods."
B, C, and D are reasonable answers. The last sentence suggests B without outright saying it (could be too close to a fact for our purposes, though). There are no other reasonable conclusions to make related to the 9% statistic than what C says. If we're saying the private sector as whole isn't considered a consumer, then I can accept D's explanation - but I think that distinction is splitting hairs.

text_answer.content:
Vocabulary sentence 1 uses pathos as an adjective when it is a noun. Fun fact that I just learned, pathos does indeed have an adjective form and it is 'pathetic,' which clarifies some of the confusion I've had over the use of the word in certain literary texts.

I question that last paragraph. Advertisers would lie to our faces about the capabilities of products if they were allowed to. For example, most 'medical professionals' in healthcare advertisements are pair actors and '4 out of 5 dentists agree' is a meaningless statistic.
A minor part of our job is making sure students can think critically about the world around them; suggesting advertisers a generally responsible and truthful is inaccurate and suggests students should trust the ads they see have their best interest in mind (which they do not). This affects key details question 3.

For the inference, I actually think answer B isn't supported enough by the passage as written. There's nothing here that suggests companies are investing in psychological research. Rather, the best we can conclude is that they use the research that exists to its greatest effect.
An alternative "Pathos, logos, and ethos aren't limited to advertising." The entire passage is about advertising and the tools that go into it, so anything outside of this sector is fair game for an inference.

For the inference, I'm not sure I like any of the answers. Answer A isn't really supported since the "battle of the fly" didn't definitively change the mind of Levi, despite the general populace's preferences. This reluctance to change was even through fashion designers and usage during WWI. It took over a decade to even get them to include the zipper and then two more to get them to prioritize it.
A better inference might be "Ease of use is a strong motivator behind societal attitudes." This recognizes both the seemingly contradictory initial hesitancy and eventual adoption of zippers in clothing. This does overlap with prompt 1, but I'm not a fan of that prompt.
